{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"80b929ef-7102-4b46-af60-72de91bb8a53","content":"## Two Breaking Changes in C# 15\n\n### 1. `DynamicOps.cs` — Stricter static binding for `&&` with `dynamic`\n\nC# 15 now **statically validates** the left operand's type when using `&&`/`||`, even when the other operand is `dynamic`. Previously, the entire expression was deferred to the runtime binder.\n\n`&&` is synthesized from `operator false` + `operator &`. Your `IFilter` defines `operator true`/`operator false` but **no `operator &`**, so the compiler rejects the compound `&&`.\n\n**Fix:** Add the missing `&` operator to the interface:\n```csharp\ninterface IFilter\n{\n    static IFilter operator &(IFilter x, IFilter y) => x;\n    static bool operator true(IFilter x) => true;\n    static bool operator false(IFilter x) => false;\n}\n```\nOr cast `left` to `dynamic`: `var combined = (dynamic)left && right;`\n\n---\n\n### 2. `RefHelper.cs` — Missing predefined type for `ref readonly` lambda inference\n\n`CS0518` means the compiler needs a well-known BCL type that isn't present in your target framework. In C# 15, **natural delegate types for `ref readonly`-returning lambdas** require new runtime infrastructure (a synthesized delegate representation) only available in .NET 11's BCL.\n\nThis typically happens when you're using the C# 15 compiler but **targeting an older TFM** (e.g., `net8.0` or `net9.0`).\n\n**Fix — option A:** Target .NET 11:\n```xml\n<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>\n```\n\n**Fix — option B:** Declare an explicit delegate type (works on older TFMs):\n```csharp\ndelegate ref readonly int RefReadonlyFunc();\n\npublic static void M()\n{\n    RefReadonlyFunc fn = () => ref value;\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7891468f-046f-4513-b1c5-0167631ee4c8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two new compiler errors they're getting after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze both cases:\n\n**Case 1: `DynamicOps.cs` - `left && right` with dynamic**\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there's a breaking change related to how the compiler handles short-circuiting operators (`&&` / `||`) when one operand is `dynamic`. \n\nThe issue here is that `&&` is a short-circuiting operator that requires both `operator &` and `operator true`/`operator false` to be defined. \n\nWhen one operand is `dynamic`, the compiler needs to resolve the `true`/`false` operators at compile time for the left operand to determine whether to short-circuit. Earlier versions deferred this to runtime, but C# 15 now performs stricter compile-time checks on these operators with dynamic operands.\n\nThe `IFilter` interface defines `static bool operator true` and `static bool operator false`, but doesn't define `operator &`. Meanwhile, `CompositeFilter` implements all three operators. The issue is likely that the compiler can't properly resolve which operator to use when mixing dynamic with these types. So the compiler now enforces that when `&&` involves `dynamic`, the static type must have both `operator true`/`operator false` AND `operator &` defined—the entire operation can't be deferred to runtime anymore. Since `IFilter` only defines the former but not the latter, the compiler can't construct the `&&` operation. The semantics require `x && y` to expand to `T.false(x) ? x : T.&(x, y)`, and without `operator &` on `IFilter`, that expansion fails.\n\nBut wait, `IFilter` does define `operator true`/`operator false`, so why is this still breaking? Maybe the issue is that these are defined as static interface members rather than instance operators. needs `operator &` and `operator true`/`operator false` on the same type, but `IFilter` only has the latter. I'm wondering if this is about a C# 15 breaking change where the compiler no longer permits `&&`/`||` operations mixing `dynamic` with a type that defines `operator true`/`operator false` without a corresponding `operator &`.\n\nThe workaround would be adding `operator &` to `IFilter`, casting `left` to `dynamic` as well, or switching to `&` if short-circuiting isn't required.\n\nNow looking at another issue in `RefHelper.cs` involving `ref readonly` returns in lambda expressions...\n\nThe compiler error CS0518 suggests it's looking for a predefined type that doesn't exist in the target framework. Since `ref` returning lambdas can't use standard `Func` or `Action` delegates, they need a custom delegate type to work properly.\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there might be a new predefined delegate type for ref-returning lambdas, or possibly a compiler services attribute like `RequiresLocationAttribute` that's needed to express `ref readonly` semantics in metadata. If the SDK or runtime references aren't properly aligned with .NET 11, this error would surface. types aren't available in your target framework or runtime, you hit CS0518. The solution is to target `net11.0`, define a custom delegate with `ref readonly` return explicitly, or ensure you have the latest SDK installed. Looking at both issues together, since the user upgraded to .NET 11 and C# 15, these are likely breaking changes in how the compiler handles these features. For the dynamic with `&&` case, C# 15 appears to be doing stricter static analysis on the non-dynamic operand now. The desugaring of `&&` requires both `operator true/false` and `operator &` to be present. In the older compiler behavior, when the right operand was `dynamic`, the entire operation would fall back to dynamic invocation. But the newer Roslyn version checks whether the left type supports the full `&&` pattern upfront—and since `IFilter` only has `operator true/false` without `operator &`, the compiler rejects it rather than deferring to runtime resolution. This is likely a documented breaking change in how the compiler handles short-circuit operators with dynamic operands in C# 15 or .NET 11.\n\nFor the ref-readonly lambda issue, the error CS0518 suggests a missing well-known type that's required for ref-readonly-returning delegates in C# 15—this could be a synthesized delegate type or framework attribute that isn't available in the target runtime. infer a delegate type that needs special attributes to handle `ref readonly` returns, and if those attributes aren't available in the target runtime, the compiler throws CS0518. The solution is either targeting the right .NET version or explicitly defining a delegate type with `ref readonly` return syntax. I'm also recalling that C# 10 introduced anonymous delegate types for `var` lambdas, but ref-returning lambdas likely only became supported with `var` in C# 15, requiring new runtime infrastructure to work properly. targeting an older framework that lacks the necessary runtime support for `ref readonly` lambdas with type inference. The fix would be to target `net11.0` or explicitly define a delegate type instead of relying on `var` inference. I'm reconsidering whether the missing type is actually something like `RefReadOnlyAttribute`, but that's existed since .NET Core 2.1, so it's more likely an issue with how natural delegate types handle `ref readonly` returns in their metadata. The `&&` operator gets synthesized from `operator &` combined with `operator true`/`operator false`, so when evaluating `left && right`, the compiler needs to call `operator false(left)` first to short-circuit, then `operator &(left, right)` if needed. Since `IFilter` defines the true/false operators but not the `&` operator, the compilation fails. In earlier C# versions, the compiler would fall back to a different strategy when `right` was `dynamic`, but that workaround no longer applies.","outputTokens":4799,"requestId":"C421:244C23:1E137C5:21EC882:6A07C9A2"},"id":"9e0e7f81-3035-44c3-82b6-4574f1628182","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:35:48.472Z","parentId":"0706b271-e29f-4e3a-a12d-279c356e6c69"}
